Israeli Stocks: Teva, Delek Real Estate, Elbit Systems, Isramco

-- B y   S h o s h a n n a   S o l o m o n
-- 
2011-09-26T14:53:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-26/israeli-stocks-teva-delek-real-estate-elbit-systems-isramco.html
Israel ’s TA-25 Index increased for
a second day, gaining 0.2 percent to 1,062.59 at the 4:30 close
in Tel Aviv. Investors traded about 1.1 billion shekels ($294
million) of shares and convertible securities today, according
to Tel Aviv Stock Exchange data.  The following stocks rose or fell today. Symbols are in
parentheses.  Delek Real Estate Ltd. (DLKR)   surged 20 percent, the
most since Aug. 14, to 0.165 shekel. Controlling shareholder
Isaac Tshuva reached a memorandum of understanding with holders
of the property company’s Series Dalet, Heh and Kaf-Heh bonds.  Elbit Systems Ltd. (ESLT)   increased 3.6 percent to
143.70 shekels, the highest level since Sept. 1. The board of
Israel’s largest non-government defense contractor authorized
the buyback of as many as 1 million shares over the next year.  Isramco Negev 2 LP (ISRAL IT) gained 2.1 percent to 0.392
shekel, the highest since Aug. 31. Citigroup Inc. raised its
recommendation on the oil and gas explorer to “buy” from
“hold.”  Kardan NV (KRNV)   soared 11 percent, the most since May
2009, to 8.485 shekels. The investor in water infrastructure,
property and financial services said it will spend as much as 15
million euros ($20 million) to repurchase shares.  Modiin-LP (MDINL IT) declined for the third time in four
days, dropping 1.3 percent to 0.23 shekel. The oil regulator at
the Infrastructures Ministry rejected changes to a work plan at
the Zurim license. Zerah Oil & Gas Explorations LP (ZRAHL IT),
Modiin’s partner in Zurim, lost 5.7 percent to 0.05 shekel.  Teva Pharmaceutical Industries Ltd. (TEVA)   rose 2.7
percent, the most since Aug. 16, to 133.80 shekels. The world’s
largest generic drugmaker agreed to buy the 50 percent stake it
doesn’t own in its Japanese joint venture, Teva-Kowa Pharma Co.
Ltd., from Kowa Co. for $150 million.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shoshanna Solomon in  Tel Aviv  at 
 ssolomon22@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
